"""
MKT Context Commentary -- John chapter 8
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-john-8-8.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text)
- data/translation/notes/john.json (translation reasoning)
- data/commentary/ellicott/john.json (philological and historical notes)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/john.json (chs 1-5 for continuity)

Key decisions in this range:
- Pericope adulterae (vv. 1-11): textual situation noted briefly in v.3 entry;
  treated as canonical text for commentary purposes, with historical note
- "The Evangelist" for the author throughout (matching chs 1-5)
- Tabernacles lamp ceremony as background for v.12 "light of the world" (v.20
  places the scene in the Court of Women/treasury, the very location of the ceremony)
- Ego eimi at v.24, v.28, v.58 distinguished: v.24/v.28 ambiguous; v.58 unambiguous
  claim to divine Name, hence the immediate stoning attempt
- "Not yet fifty" (v.57) connected to Levitical priestly service age (Num 4:3,47)
  rather than as a claim that Jesus was nearly 50
- Abraham's prophetic vision of "my day" (v.56) traced to Jubilees 16 and Aqedah traditions
- Roman slavery law (patria potestas; slave vs. son) as background for vv. 34-36
- Samaritan charge (v.48) treated as social insult, not theological charge
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


JOHN = {
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>Luke 21:37-38 describes Jesus's pattern during the festival week: teaching in the Temple by day, withdrawing to the Mount of Olives at night. The Evangelist assumes this practice without spelling it out; the verse is a one-line transition connecting the preceding discourse (ch. 7) to the next morning's scene. The Mount of Olives was a natural retreat -- it lay just east of the city, separated from the Temple Mount by the Kidron Valley, and was planted with olive groves that provided shade and relative seclusion from the dense crowds filling Jerusalem during festivals.</p>",

    "2": "<p>Teaching by sitting was the conventional posture for formal Jewish instruction. A rabbi stood to read Scripture and sat to expound it (Lk 4:20-21); the audience gathered around him (<em>ochlos</em>, the crowd) in the recognized relationship of students to a seated teacher. Appearing \"at dawn\" (<em>orthrou</em>) in the Temple courts signaled both urgency and public availability -- the Temple was the site of legitimate religious discourse, and presenting there was an implicit claim to speak within the recognized institutional frame.</p>",

    "3": "<p>The scribes and Pharisees bring a woman caught in adultery as a deliberate legal trap. Two points of background are essential. First, Leviticus 20:10 and Deuteronomy 22:22 require both the man and the woman to be put to death -- the conspicuous absence of the male partner suggests the situation was engineered rather than accidentally discovered. Second, by the first century, Rome had removed the Jewish right of capital execution for most offenses: the Sanhedrin retained jurisdiction over Temple violations but not ordinary capital crimes (cf. John 18:31, \"It is not lawful for us to put anyone to death\"). The trap was therefore juridical: if Jesus affirmed stoning he defied Roman law; if he opposed it he contradicted Moses.</p><p>Note on the text: the story of the woman taken in adultery (John 7:53-8:11) is absent from the earliest Greek manuscripts (Papyrus 66, Papyrus 75, Codex Vaticanus, Codex Sinaiticus) and is marked with asterisks or obeli in many later manuscripts that include it, indicating ancient scribal uncertainty about its place. Its vocabulary and style differ somewhat from the surrounding chapters. Most contemporary critical editions include it with brackets. The commentary treats it as canonical for contextual purposes while acknowledging its complex textual history.</p>",

    "4": "<p>\"Caught in the very act\" (<em>ep' autophōrō</em>) was the technical legal phrase for in flagrante detection, which was a precondition for certain Mosaic penalties. Deuteronomy 22:22-24 specifies stoning only for a betrothed woman and her partner caught in the act inside the city; the evidence requirement was intentionally high to deter capricious accusation. The specific phrasing here sharpens the legal precision of the trap: they are invoking the narrow case in which the Mosaic penalty was unambiguous. The question is designed to eliminate any legal escape route for Jesus.</p>",

    "5": "<p>The questioners invoke the relevant Mosaic texts: Leviticus 20:10 prescribes death for both parties; Deuteronomy 22:22-24 specifies stoning for the particular case of a betrothed woman. The present tense \"Moses commanded us\" (<em>eneteilato</em>) frames it as a live legal obligation. Their formulation places Jesus in a double bind: answer in favor of stoning and he has endorsed an action the Roman government reserves for itself; answer against and he has set himself against Moses. Either answer, in their reasoning, destroys his credibility with some part of his audience.</p>",

    "6": "<p>The Evangelist explicitly states the intent: to have a basis for charging Jesus (<em>kategorein</em> -- a legal term; they wanted grounds for formal accusation). Jesus's response of writing on the ground has generated speculation from earliest times -- Ambrose, Jerome, and later interpreters proposed he was writing their sins, or the relevant law, or simply making space to think -- but the Evangelist offers no explanation. The most contextually significant observation is that by stooping and writing, Jesus declined to engage their framing immediately, a culturally powerful non-response that forced them to repeat themselves (v.7).</p>",

    "7": "<p>\"Let the one among you who is without sin cast the first stone\" does not argue against capital punishment in principle; it shifts the legal question from \"what does the law require?\" to \"who is qualified to execute it?\" In Jewish legal procedure, the witnesses to a capital offense were required to cast the first stones (Deut 17:7). Jesus's statement addresses the accusers precisely as (pretended) witnesses, and the requirement of moral integrity for that role was not foreign to Jewish legal thought -- Deuteronomy 19:15-20 describes false witnesses facing the same penalty their testimony would have imposed. The challenge is not sentimental; it is technically pointed.</p>",

    "8": "<p>Stooping to write a second time extended the pause, giving the accusers time to process what had been said without forcing a public confrontation. In a high honor-shame culture, the space to withdraw quietly -- rather than face further public challenge -- was socially important. The writing created a focal point that allowed the crowd's attention to rest somewhere other than on the accusers' faces as they considered their position.</p>",

    "9": "<p>The departure of the older men first follows honor-shame logic precisely: the senior members of the group had the most accumulated social standing to protect and the most public exposure if they were seen to be unable to answer. In a society where an elder's authority depended on his visible moral standing, remaining to argue after a challenge to their moral qualification would have compounded the exposure. The sequence -- elders first, then the younger -- traces the hierarchy of shame from top down.</p>",

    "10": "<p>\"Woman\" (<em>gynai</em>) is the same respectful address Jesus uses in speaking to his mother at Cana (2:4) and at the cross (19:26), and to Mary Magdalene at the tomb (20:13). It carries no contempt in Greek; it is the standard address to an adult woman in a formal or elevated register. The question \"Has no one condemned you?\" (<em>katekrinen</em>) uses legal vocabulary -- the formal verdict of condemnation. Jesus is confirming the legal outcome before pronouncing his own non-sentence.</p>",

    "11": "<p>\"Neither do I condemn you\" (<em>oud' egō se katakrinō</em>) is not a verdict of innocence but a decision not to exercise condemnation -- issued by one who, the narrative has now implied, was the only person present actually qualified to cast the first stone. The command to \"go and sin no more\" is the same structure Jesus uses at 5:14 after healing the paralytic: mercy extended alongside a moral demand. The scene does not license antinomianism; the wrongdoing is acknowledged as real. The combination -- mercy without moral dismissal -- was not self-evidently Jewish (the law required penalty) or Greco-Roman (moral permissiveness was an alternative).</p>",

    "12": "<p>Jesus's claim to be \"the light of the world\" was made during the Feast of Tabernacles (see 7:2, 37), and the spatial location confirmed in v.20 -- the treasury, within the Court of Women -- was the precise site of the festival's most dramatic ceremony. Each night of Tabernacles, four enormous golden lampstands (<em>menorot</em>) were erected in the Court of Women, reportedly so bright that \"there was not a courtyard in Jerusalem that did not reflect their light\" (Mishnah Sukkah 5:3). The celebration around these lamps -- music, torch-dancing, the pouring of water at the altar -- was one of the most intense liturgical events of the Jewish year. To announce \"I am the light of the world\" in the court where those lamps stood, at the festival that celebrated divine light, was a claim of exact correspondence: he is what the ceremony enacts.</p><p>The background also includes Isaiah's servant as \"a light for the nations\" (Isa 42:6; 49:6) and the promise that \"the people walking in darkness have seen a great light\" (Isa 9:2). The Evangelist's audience would have heard both registers simultaneously.</p>",

    "13": "<p>The Pharisees' objection is a technical point of Jewish legal procedure: self-testimony was inadmissible without corroboration. The Mishnah later codified this principle explicitly (Sanhedrin 9:2: \"no one may testify concerning himself\"), but the rule was established in practice long before. Their challenge -- \"your witness is not true\" (<em>alēthēs</em>) -- is a procedural dismissal, not a substantive rebuttal of what he said. The legal register throughout vv. 13-18 is deliberate; Jesus's responses engage on the same juridical terms.</p>",

    "14": "<p>Jesus's counter-claim rests on unique epistemic grounds: he knows his own origin and destination in a way no outside witness could verify or deny. In standard Jewish legal procedure, the credibility of a witness was assessed by whether others could check the facts. Jesus claims his testimony is self-validating because its subject matter -- his divine origin -- is inaccessible to ordinary verification. This is not an evasion of the legal standard; it is a claim that the standard itself was calibrated for human testimony and cannot contain what he is asserting.</p>",

    "15": "<p>\"You judge by human standards\" -- literally, \"according to the flesh\" (<em>kata tēn sarka</em>). In Jewish thought, fleshly or worldly judgment was the mode of the courts and legal institutions: assessing externally visible evidence, weighing testimony by social standing, calculating by the standards of the present age. Jesus's claim to \"judge no one\" in this mode does not mean he renders no verdicts, but that his verdicts, when issued, operate on different grounds than those of the institutional questioners.</p>",

    "16": "<p>The claim that his judgments are true because he does not stand alone but with the Father introduces the concept of divine co-judgment. In Jewish legal thought, a legitimate verdict required proper authority and proper process. Jesus appeals to the co-presence of the Father -- the highest conceivable authority -- as the ground for the validity of his verdicts. This is not a formality; it reframes the entire legal proceeding: his opponents are not adjudicating him; he and the Father are adjudicating them.</p>",

    "17": "<p>The two-witness rule derives from Deuteronomy 17:6 and 19:15: \"A matter must be established by the testimony of two or three witnesses.\" Jesus quotes it back to the Pharisees as \"your law\" -- a phrase he uses several times in the Fourth Gospel (10:34; 15:25) that carries a slight distancing. He is not disowning the law but sharpening the point: the rule they are invoking to discredit him, he now applies to satisfy on his own terms.</p>",

    "18": "<p>Jesus names his two witnesses: himself and the Father. This collapses the human two-witness requirement into a divine-human pair that the legal framework cannot accommodate. The form is correct (two witnesses); the content is unprecedented (one is divine). The Pharisees cannot simply dismiss the formula without dismissing the law's requirement; but accepting it means accepting Jesus's claim about the Father's identity as his witness. The entrapment has been reversed: they are now in the juridical corner.</p>",

    "19": "<p>\"Where is your Father?\" expects a human father whose corroboration could be sought -- a man who could appear and testify. The question is reasonable within their frame: two-witness law requires locatable, cross-examinable witnesses. Jesus's reply -- \"you do not know me or my Father\" -- breaks the frame. The ignorance of his identity and the ignorance of his Father's identity are not separable; knowing the Son is the only access to the Father (cf. 14:9). For an audience steeped in Jewish theology where knowing God was the central aspiration of covenant life, this claim was not modest.</p>",

    "20": "<p>The treasury (<em>gazophylakion</em>) is identified by Josephus and the Synoptic Gospels as the area in the Court of Women where thirteen trumpet-shaped collection chests stood for voluntary offerings (Mk 12:41-44; Josephus, <em>War</em> 5.5.2). The Court of Women was the largest open court in the Temple complex, accessible to all Jewish adults regardless of gender; it was also the precise location of the Tabernacles lamp ceremony (Mishnah Sukkah 5:2-4). The geographical note is therefore not incidental: the Evangelist is placing Jesus's \"I am the light of the world\" claim (v.12) in the court where the festival lampstands stood, in the room where the offerings were placed -- Temple space at its most public and most symbolically charged.</p><p>\"His hour had not yet come\" is a recurring Johannine phrase (2:4; 7:30) signaling divine timing. No arrest occurs because the narrative is under different governance than Roman or Pharisaic scheduling.</p>",

    "21": "<p>\"Die in your sin\" (<em>en tē hamartia hymōn</em>) inverts the standard hope of Jewish eschatology. The covenant promise was that Israel would be forgiven, cleansed, and vindicated at the end. Dying <em>in</em> one's sin -- unreleased from its guilt -- was the condition of those outside the covenant, or of Israel under judgment for covenant unfaithfulness (Ezek 18:18, 24). To speak this to Jerusalem's religious leaders in the Temple during a festival was a public prophetic declaration of covenant failure.</p>",

    "22": "<p>The speculation that Jesus might kill himself reflects both a literalistic misreading and a social contempt. Suicide was viewed with strong disapproval in Second Temple Judaism; Josephus explicitly condemns it (<em>War</em> 3.8.5), arguing against it on theological grounds during the Jewish Revolt. The suggestion \"will he kill himself?\" is not a neutral question; it implies that such an end would explain why they could not follow -- they would not go to Sheol, the realm of the dead, by their own choosing.</p>",

    "23": "<p>The cosmological contrast -- from below/from above, of this world/not of this world -- uses spatial categories familiar from Jewish apocalyptic. The Dead Sea Scrolls distinguish the sons of light from the sons of darkness and organize creation into heavenly and earthly domains with corresponding moral allegiances. The Wisdom tradition similarly distinguished wisdom from above (Prov 8; Wis 9) from the wisdom of the present age. Jesus's statement locates the Pharisees' incomprehension structurally, not just morally: they cannot receive what he says because their cognitive and moral orientation is calibrated to this order rather than the one from which he comes.</p>",

    "24": "<p>\"If you do not believe that I am he (<em>hoti egō eimi</em>), you will die in your sins\" -- the Greek is ego eimi without a predicate, the same construction as in the Septuagint's translation of God's self-disclosure in Isaiah 43:10 (\"that you may know and believe me, and understand that <em>egō eimi</em>\") and Exodus 3:14. Whether the audience here fully recognizes the divine-Name register is left ambiguous -- v.27 says they did not understand -- but the formulation is deliberate. The Evangelist is placing the stakes in eschatological terms: to die in sin is to be outside the shelter that only this identity can provide.</p>",

    "25": "<p>\"Who are you?\" -- the blunt identity challenge is a recognition that Jesus has been making claims his interlocutors are not prepared to accept. His answer, variously translated, signals continuity: what he has been saying from the beginning is his identity. The response is less evasive than impatient -- he has been identifying himself throughout (1:51; 3:16-17; 4:25-26; 5:19-30; 6:35-51; 7:37-38), and the question now suggests willful incomprehension rather than genuine inquiry.</p>",

    "26": "<p>The appeal to the one who sent him (<em>ho pempsas me</em>) is a standard category of Jewish agency law: a commissioned agent acted with the full authority of the sender and was understood to be the sender's authorized representative. The concept (<em>shaliach</em> principle) meant that receiving or rejecting the agent was equivalent to receiving or rejecting the principal. Jesus's claim to speak only what he has heard from the Father positions him as the ultimate <em>shaliach</em>, whose message carries divine authority not his own.</p>",

    "27": "<p>The parenthetical note -- \"they did not understand that he was speaking about the Father\" -- is one of the Evangelist's clarifying asides for the reader. It explains why the dialogue appears to be at cross-purposes: the audience is hearing Jesus's references to \"the one who sent me\" and his \"Father\" as rhetorical or metaphorical speech, not as claims about the actual God of Israel. The misunderstanding is not feigned by the Evangelist; it reflects the genuine difficulty of Jesus's speech, which operates simultaneously on human and divine registers.</p>",

    "28": "<p>\"When you have lifted up the Son of Man\" (<em>hypsōsēte</em>) uses the same verb as 3:14 (Moses lifting up the serpent) and 12:32-33 (\"I, when I am lifted up from the earth, will draw all people to myself\" -- which the Evangelist glosses as the manner of his death). The crucifixion is described with the vocabulary of exaltation, a paradox that would have registered against the Roman understanding of crucifixion as maximum degradation. In the Numbers background (21:8-9), the lifted-up serpent was the instrument of healing, not punishment. The language holds both meanings together.</p>",

    "29": "<p>\"The one who sent me is with me; he has not left me alone\" reflects the covenant assurance language given to the patriarchs and to Israel's leaders: God's promise to be \"with\" Moses (Exod 3:12), Joshua (Josh 1:5), and the exiles (Isa 43:2, 5). \"I always do what pleases him\" echoes the language of Psalm 40:8 (LXX): \"I delight to do your will, O my God.\" The Evangelist presents Jesus's obedience not as constraint but as the defining characteristic of his relationship with the Father -- the content that fills the form of \"the one who sent me.\"</p>",

    "30": "<p>\"Even as he spoke, many believed in him\" -- a brief summary note without character development. The Evangelist does not explain what about this particular exchange produced belief, but the pattern throughout ch. 7-8 has been a gradual polarization of the crowd: some hostile, some curious, some persuaded. The note prepares for the following dialogue (vv. 31-47), which is addressed specifically to \"those Jews who had believed him\" -- a group that, paradoxically, will resist his teaching and end the chapter attempting to stone him.</p>",

    "31": "<p>The condition for genuine discipleship -- \"if you hold to my teaching\" (<em>ean hymeis meinēte en tō logō</em>) -- uses the verb <em>menō</em> (abide, remain), which carries weight throughout the Fourth Gospel. It is not merely intellectual assent but sustained dwelling in a way of life. The covenant-loyalty language is relevant: in Jewish thought, faithfulness was not a one-time decision but an ongoing orientation of the whole person toward Torah. Jesus displaces Torah as the content of that loyalty with his own teaching (<em>logos</em>).</p>",

    "32": "<p>\"The truth will set you free\" has become a culturally detached proverb, but in its context it carries a specific Jewish freight. \"Truth\" (<em>alētheia</em>) in John's usage is not abstract correctness but the real, the reliable, the trustworthy -- the quality of God and his word (17:17, \"Your word is truth\"). \"Free\" (<em>eleutheroi</em>) in a world where a significant portion of the population were slaves or freed persons with limited status was not a merely spiritual metaphor; freedom was a concrete social category. Jesus is promising that what Torah itself could not fully accomplish -- release from the deeper bondage of sin -- his word accomplishes.</p>",

    "33": "<p>\"We are Abraham's descendants and have never been slaves of anyone\" is historically striking. Israel had been enslaved in Egypt for 430 years (the central narrative of their identity), deported to Assyria and Babylon, and currently lived under Roman occupation. The claim makes sense only as an assertion about covenantal status rather than political reality: as Abraham's seed, they understood themselves to be God's chosen people, whose ultimate dignity was not negated by political circumstances. Paul engages exactly this claim in Galatians 4:21-31, drawing the distinction between children of the slave woman and children of the free woman within the Abrahamic line itself.</p>",

    "34": "<p>\"Everyone who sins is a slave to sin\" -- the present participle (<em>poiōn tēn hamartian</em>, the one doing sin) emphasizes ongoing practice, not a single act. In the Roman world the audience inhabited, slavery was the dominant metaphor for any non-voluntary, self-perpetuating condition. Approximately 15-25% of the Roman Empire's population were slaves; manumission was possible but created a dependent relationship (<em>libertus</em>) with the former master that was rarely fully free. Jesus is diagnosing a condition as pervasive as Roman slavery itself, but one the law of Moses had not eliminated.</p>",

    "35": "<p>Roman household law (<em>patria potestas</em>) sharply distinguished the legal standing of the slave from that of the son. A slave had no permanent membership in the household: he could be sold, rented out, or freed at the master's will; his position was entirely contingent on the owner's pleasure. A son, by contrast, belonged to the household permanently by blood and legal right; even if temporarily sent away, he could not be sold out of the family. The social world of Jesus's audience would have grasped the distinction immediately.</p>",

    "36": "<p>Manumission -- legal release from slavery -- in the Roman world was granted by the paterfamilias, the male head of the household, and required a formal legal act. Jesus's claim that \"if the Son sets you free, you will be free indeed\" uses the exact institutional logic: only the son (as heir and authorized family representative) can grant the kind of freedom that changes actual legal status. Informal escape or self-liberation did not produce freedom in law. The claim positions the Son as the one authorized to alter the fundamental condition of those under sin's ownership.</p>",

    "37": "<p>The acknowledgment that they are Abraham's physical descendants is conceded; what is denied is that this descent conveys the moral inheritance of Abraham. The prophetic tradition frequently attacked the assumption that ethnic lineage guaranteed covenantal standing: Isaiah 51:1-2 calls Israel to \"look to Abraham your father\" not as a genealogical comfort but as a model of faith; Jeremiah 9:25-26 pronounces judgment on those who are circumcised in body but not in heart. John the Baptist had already made the same move at the Jordan: \"God can raise up children to Abraham from these stones\" (Matt 3:9).</p>",

    "38": "<p>The two-source contrast -- \"what I have seen in the Father's presence\" vs. \"what you have heard from your father\" -- introduces the father-of-the-audience theme that will culminate in v.44. The Evangelist's language for Jesus's knowledge is visual and intimate: he has <em>seen</em> things in the Father's immediate presence, the kind of privileged knowledge that a son in the father's workshop has of the father's work (cf. 5:19-20). The audience, by contrast, are acting on what they have <em>heard</em> from a father who will prove to be the devil.</p>",

    "39": "<p>\"If you were Abraham's children, you would do what Abraham did\" inverts the ethnic claim: Abrahamic descent is defined by Abrahamic behavior, not merely physical lineage. The Jewish interpretive tradition actually agreed with this in principle -- Philo describes Abraham as the model of faith-in-action, and Paul (Gal 3:7-9) uses the same argument. What Abraham \"did\" in Jewish memory was believe God, welcome strangers (Gen 18), and obey even when it was costly. The accusers' determination to kill Jesus -- a man who has told them the truth -- is the anti-Abraham behavior Jesus is pointing to.</p>",

    "40": "<p>\"A man who has told you the truth that I heard from God\" -- Jesus describes himself in precisely the terms used for a prophet: one who hears from God and declares it faithfully. The claim \"Abraham did not do this\" is pointed: hospitality to divine messengers was Abraham's defining virtue (Gen 18:1-8). The desire to kill the messenger who brings true words from God is the antithesis of Abrahamic welcome. Prophetic tradition routinely described Israel's violence against God's emissaries as the culmination of covenant unfaithfulness (2 Chr 36:15-16).</p>",

    "41": "<p>\"We are not illegitimate children\" (<em>ek porneias</em>, literally \"of fornication\") has been read as a possible response to circulating accusations that Jesus was born of illicit union -- a charge that appears in later rabbinic polemic (Talmud Sanhedrin 106a, Yevamot 49b). If the Evangelist is aware of this tradition, the line registers as a slur deflected back at the opponent. More directly, the claim asserts covenantal legitimacy: they are not spiritual bastards born of idolatry (the \"fornication\" of which the prophets accuse Israel when it pursues other gods -- Ezek 16; Hos 1-3).</p>",

    "42": "<p>The claim \"I have come here from God\" (<em>ek tou theou exēlthon</em>) places Jesus in the category of divinely dispatched agents. Jewish angelology and the Wisdom tradition both described heavenly figures who were sent (<em>apostellō</em>) from God's presence to accomplish his purposes. But unlike a commissioned prophet or angel, Jesus claims not merely to have received a commission but to have originated from God's own being -- \"I have not come on my own\" distinguishes the mission from independent initiative and grounds it in divine sending.</p>",

    "43": "<p>\"Unable to hear\" (<em>ou dynasthe akouein</em>) echoes the prophetic diagnosis of Israel's spiritual deafness. Isaiah 6:9-10 describes YHWH's commissioning of Isaiah: \"Go and tell this people: Be ever hearing, but never understanding.\" This text becomes programmatic in the Synoptic tradition for explaining why parables produce incomprehension (Mk 4:12) and why many reject Jesus (Matt 13:14-15). The Evangelist presents the same dynamic: the inability to hear is not merely intellectual stubbornness but a moral condition -- a consequence of alignment with a different father.</p>",

    "44": "<p>\"You belong to your father, the devil\" is the culmination of the father-language running through vv. 38-44. The identification of the devil as \"a murderer from the beginning\" reaches back to Genesis: either the serpent's introduction of death into creation through the fall (Gen 3; Wis 2:24 makes the identification explicit: \"through the devil's envy death entered the world\") or to the murder of Abel, which Jewish tradition sometimes associated with demonic instigation. The characterization of the devil as a liar and \"the father of lies\" was not a Johannine invention -- Qumran texts describe the \"spirit of deceit\" as the source of falsehood in human hearts (1QS 3:18-21).</p><p>In a culture where one's moral character was understood to derive from one's lineage, the charge struck at the deepest level of identity: not just that they were wrong, but that their wrongness was genealogical.</p>",

    "45": "<p>The logic of v.45 is pointed: because Jesus tells the truth, they do not believe him. In a patron-client and honor-shame culture, credibility derived from social standing, group membership, and approved authorities. An outsider claiming to speak truth over against established teachers would be evaluated through those social filters before the content was assessed. Jesus inverts the expected order: the truth itself should command assent; their rejection of it reveals a prior alignment with the source of falsehood.</p>",

    "46": "<p>\"Can any of you prove me guilty of sin?\" (<em>elegchei</em> -- a juridical verb, to convict, expose, refute) is a legal challenge: produce evidence for a specific charge. The silence of the crowd at this point is significant. Throughout the chapter they have had procedural objections but no substantive charge. The challenge exposes that the hostility is not based on demonstrable wrongdoing but on a resistance that Jesus has just located in a deeper source.</p>",

    "47": "<p>\"Whoever belongs to God hears what God says\" -- the concept of belonging to God (<em>ek tou theou</em>, of-God origin) draws on covenant language: Israel's identity was defined by being God's possession (<em>segullah</em>, Exod 19:5; Deut 7:6). To belong to God was to be attuned to God's voice. The Shepherd discourse (ch. 10) will develop exactly this image: the sheep who belong to the shepherd recognize his voice; the refusal to hear is itself diagnostic of non-belonging. Hearing, in Hebrew and Greek thought alike, was not passive reception but active, obedient response.</p>",

    "48": "<p>The dual charge -- \"you are a Samaritan and demon-possessed\" -- deploys two separate social insults. The Samaritan charge was a powerful slur in Jerusalem; it implied cultural contamination, religious syncretism, or descent from the half-Jewish, half-Gentile population installed in the north after the Assyrian deportation (2 Kgs 17:24-41). To call a Galilean a Samaritan was to question his ethnic and religious authenticity. Separately, \"he has a demon\" (<em>daimonion echei</em>) was a standard charge against anyone who claimed unusual authority or knowledge: it attributed the ability to something demonic rather than divine, which functioned as a social-epistemological circuit breaker against unauthorized truth-tellers.</p>",

    "49": "<p>\"I honor my Father and you dishonor me\" places the exchange within the framework of honor reciprocity. In patronage culture, honoring one's patron (and his authorized representative) was both a moral and a social obligation; dishonoring the patron's agent dishonored the patron himself. Jesus's response to the Samaritan charge is thus not defensive but theological: the question is not his ethnic origin but his patron, and his patron's honor is implicated in how they treat him. The charge of being Samaritan is irrelevant; the charge of demon possession is false because it inverts the actual structure of his allegiances.</p>",

    "50": "<p>\"I am not seeking glory for myself\" stands in explicit contrast to the honor-seeking behavior Jesus had criticized in 5:44 -- those who receive glory from one another and do not seek the glory that comes from God. The one who seeks Jesus's glory is the Father, who is also the judge. This collapses the conventional honor-game: the only honor that matters in the long run is the Father's assessment, and the Father is both patron and judge. The audience's withholding of honor or bestowing of dishonor is therefore ultimately irrelevant to the question of Jesus's standing.</p>",

    "51": "<p>\"Whoever keeps my word will never see death\" -- the promise moves from honor to life, and from legal category to eschatological reality. \"Keep\" (<em>tēreō</em>) is covenant-loyalty language: in the Hebrew Scriptures it is used of keeping Torah, keeping the commandments, keeping the covenant. Here the object is transferred from Torah to Jesus's word. In Second Temple eschatology, the expectation of resurrection meant that death was not the final word for the righteous; the innovation is locating the guarantee of that future in present alignment with Jesus's <em>logos</em> rather than in Torah observance.</p>",

    "52": "<p>The audience again reads the promise literally: Abraham died; the prophets died; how can anyone who keeps his word escape death? The misunderstanding follows the same pattern as Nicodemus on re-birth (3:4) and the Samaritan woman on living water (4:15). The Evangelist uses these literal misreadings not to mock the interlocutors but to clarify the depth of the claim: Jesus is not speaking of biological death, which they can see, but of a category of death that biological death merely shadows. The citation of Abraham and the prophets as counter-examples assumes the highest possible standard -- and Jesus will shortly claim to exceed it.</p>",

    "53": "<p>\"Are you greater than our father Abraham?\" is the question the whole dialogue has been pressing toward. In Jewish honor culture, to rank oneself above Abraham was an almost inconceivable claim; Abraham was the founding patriarch, the friend of God (<em>Isa 41:8; Jas 2:23</em>), the recipient of the covenant, the model of faith. The prophets died too: the challenge names the greatest figures of Israel's history and dares Jesus to claim superiority. The question is derisive, but it sets up exactly the answer Jesus gives.</p>",

    "54": "<p>\"My Father, whom you claim as your God\" -- the possessive distinction is sharp. \"Your God\" was the standard covenantal formula (\"I will be your God and you will be my people,\" Lev 26:12; Jer 7:23). Jesus accepts that the Father is the God they profess, and affirms that the Father is the one who glorifies him. The claim is not merely that his Father exists, but that the one they call their covenant God has taken Jesus's side -- a charge with profound implications for their own covenantal standing.</p>",

    "55": "<p>\"If I said I did not know him, I would be a liar like you\" -- the Evangelist does not soften this. The charge of lying (<em>pseudēs</em>) was significant in any culture; in the Jewish context it carried additional weight because the Torah's prohibitions on false witness were tied to the integrity of the entire legal and social system. To be a liar was not merely a personal failing but a structural threat to communal order. Jesus's claim to know the Father and keep his word is simultaneously a claim to integrity and an accusation: their denial of his knowledge is itself the falsehood.</p>",

    "56": "<p>\"Your father Abraham rejoiced at the thought of seeing my day\" draws on Jewish traditions about Abraham's prophetic vision of the messianic age. Several texts from the Second Temple period describe Abraham as having received prophetic foreknowledge of the redemptive future: Jubilees 16:16-19 describes Abraham's joy at the birth of Isaac as an anticipation of Israel's future; 4 Ezra 3:14 says God revealed \"the end of the times\" to Abraham; 2 Baruch 4:4 describes Abraham seeing \"the age to come.\" The binding of Isaac (the Aqedah, Gen 22) was also read as a prophetic anticipation of redemption in early Jewish exegesis.</p><p>A secondary resonance: the name Isaac (<em>yitzhak</em>) means \"he laughs\" or \"he rejoices\"; Abraham and Sarah's laughter at the birth of the promised son (Gen 17:17; 21:6) was retrospectively read as joy at the promise's fulfilment. \"He saw it and was glad\" may echo this tradition.</p>",

    "57": "<p>\"You are not yet fifty years old and you have seen Abraham?\" The fifty-year threshold is not arbitrary. In Numbers 4:3, 47 and 8:25, fifty was the upper age limit for Levitical priestly service in the Tabernacle. The audience's appeal to fifty does not necessarily imply they thought Jesus was nearly fifty; it invokes a culturally significant age marker for the full range of active adult life. Their rhetorical point is that his claimed encounter with Abraham is impossible given how few years he has lived.</p>",

    "58": "<p>\"Before Abraham was born, I am\" (<em>prin Abraam genesthai, egō eimi</em>) -- the grammar is deliberately asymmetrical: Abraham \"came into being\" (<em>genesthai</em>, aorist, a historical event with a beginning), while Jesus simply \"I am\" (<em>eimi</em>, present without temporal limit). The Septuagint of Exodus 3:14 translates God's self-disclosure to Moses as <em>egō eimi ho ōn</em> (\"I am the one who is\"), and Isaiah 43:10, 25; 46:4; 48:12 use <em>egō eimi</em> as a divine self-identification formula throughout. The phrase had been used earlier in the chapter (vv. 24, 28) with possible ambiguity; here the context removes it: the audience's immediate response is to pick up stones for blasphemy.</p><p>Jewish law required stoning for blasphemy (Lev 24:16), and the Mishnah Sanhedrin 7:5 specifies that blasphemy required explicitly pronouncing the divine Name. The audience's reaction confirms that this is exactly what they heard.</p>",

    "59": "<p>The immediate attempt to stone him confirms that the audience understood the claim of v.58 as blasphemy -- an explicit invocation of the divine Name. Stoning was the prescribed penalty under Leviticus 24:16, and the crowd's spontaneous action (rather than waiting for a formal trial) was a mob-justice response to what they perceived as an unambiguous public offense against God. \"Jesus hid himself\" is narrated without elaboration; the Evangelist offers no mechanism. Some ancient interpreters read it as miraculous concealment; others as movement through a crowd that had not yet organized its attack. The theological point is in the continuation: his hour had not yet come, and no stone-throwing crowd determines its timing.</p>",
  }
}


